The passage has been obscured by a false reading; and Halm has not quite seized the full meaning, or he would not have inserted ⁴ ut ' before ‘ moenibus! The walls include the whole, the houses, public places, and the men who compose the state. Each state had of course land outside the walls, but it was the old Italian fashion to live in the city, and to go out to cultivate the laud. The city wall contained the state, for when the wall was broken down, the political com- munity was at the mercy of the conqueror, and was dispersed or enslaved. Such was one of the forms of social existence, in which the notion of State was inseparable from that of Urbs.
